# Supabase client values (required for persisting campaigns)
# Copy this file to `.env.local` and fill in your Supabase project values.

# Example environment variables used by the app
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project.supabase.co
VITE_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...

# Notes:
# - The app expects these exact variable names. If you use a different name (for example
#   VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY), update `src/app/lib/supabase.ts` accordingly.
# - After creating `.env.local` restart your dev server (Vite) so the variables are picked up.

# Server-side Supabase environment variables. Copy the real values from the
# Supabase Dashboard Connect dialog and never commit the secret key.
SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project.supabase.co
SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...
SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...
SUPABASE_JWKS_URL=https://your-project.supabase.co/auth/v1/.well-known/jwks.json

# Notes:
# - `SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY` must be kept private. Do not commit it to source control.
# - `SUPABASE_JWKS_URL` is used to verify user JWTs for auth modes like `user`.
# - If you use publishable or secret auth modes outside of `user`, add
#   `verify_jwt = false` under [functions] in `supabase/config.toml`.
# - After creating `.env.local`, restart your dev server or Supabase function runner.
#
# Apply the database schema so the `public.campaigns` table exists:
# 1) Supabase Dashboard: open SQL editor and run the contents of `supabase.schema.sql`.
# 2) Or via psql (replace DATABASE_URL with your connection):
#    psql "$DATABASE_URL" -f supabase.schema.sql
# 3) If you're using the Supabase CLI and a local DB, run the appropriate commands to
#    apply the SQL file (for example, `supabase db reset` or import the SQL).
